# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: raman-spectroscopy
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] Light travels through the sample under a conventional microscope as far into the specimen as it can penetrate, while a confocal microscope only focuses a smaller beam of light at one narrow depth level at a time.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] The CLSM achieves a controlled and highly limited depth of field.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] The principle of confocal imaging was patented in 1957 by Marvin Minsky and aims to overcome some limitations of traditional wide-field fluorescence microscopes.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] In a conventional (i.e., wide-field) fluorescence microscope, the entire specimen is flooded evenly in light from a light source.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] All parts of the sample can be excited at the same time and the resulting fluorescence is detected by the microscope's photodetector or camera including a large unfocused background part.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] In contrast, a confocal microscope uses point illumination (see Point Spread Function) and a pinhole in an optically conjugate plane in front of the detector to eliminate out-of-focus signal – the name "confocal" stems from this configuration.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] As only light produced by fluorescence very close to the focal plane can be detected, the image's optical resolution, particularly in the sample depth direction, is much better than that of wide-field microscopes.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] However, as much of the light from sample fluorescence is blocked at the pinhole, this increased resolution is at the cost of decreased signal intensity – so long exposures are often required.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] To offset this drop in signal after the *pinhole*, the light intensity is detected by a sensitive detector, usually a photomultiplier tube (PMT) or avalanche photodiode, transforming the light signal into an electrical one.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] As only one point in the sample is illuminated at a time, 2D or 3D imaging requires scanning over a regular raster (i.e. a rectangular pattern of parallel scanning lines) in the specimen.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] The beam is scanned across the sample in the horizontal plane by using one or more (servo controlled) oscillating mirrors.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] This scanning method usually has a low reaction latency and the scan speed can be varied.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] Slower scans provide a better signal-to-noise ratio, resulting in better contrast.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] The achievable thickness of the focal plane is defined mostly by the wavelength of the used light divided by the numerical aperture of the objective lens, but also by the optical properties of the specimen.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] The thin optical sectioning possible makes these types of microscopes particularly good at 3D imaging and surface profiling of samples.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] Successive slices make up a 'z-stack', which can either be processed to create a 3D image, or it is merged into a 2D stack (predominately the maximum pixel intensity is taken, other common methods include using the standard deviation or summing the pixels).
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] Confocal microscopy provides the capacity for direct, noninvasive, serial optical sectioning of intact, thick, living specimens with a minimum of sample preparation as well as a marginal improvement in lateral resolution compared to wide-field microscopy.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] Biological samples are often treated with fluorescent dyes to make selected objects visible.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] However, the actual dye concentration can be low to minimize the disturbance of biological systems: some instruments can track single fluorescent molecules.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] Also, transgenic techniques can create organisms that produce their own fluorescent chimeric molecules (such as a fusion of GFP, green fluorescent protein with the protein of interest).
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] Confocal microscopes work on the principle of point excitation in the specimen (diffraction limited spot) and point detection of the resulting fluorescent signal.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] A pinhole at the detector provides a physical barrier that blocks out-of-focus fluorescence.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] Only the in-focus, or central spot of the Airy disk, is recorded.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] Each of these classes of confocal microscope have particular advantages and disadvantages.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] Most systems are either optimized for recording speed (i.e. video capture) or high spatial resolution.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] Confocal laser scanning microscopes can have a programmable sampling density and very high resolutions while Nipkow and PAM use a fixed sampling density defined by the camera's resolution.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] Imaging frame rates are typically slower for single point laser scanning systems than spinning-disk or PAM systems.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] Commercial spinning-disk confocal microscopes achieve frame rates of over 50 per second – a desirable feature for dynamic observations such as live cell imaging.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] Cutting-edge development of confocal laser scanning microscopy now allows better than standard video rate (60 frames per second) imaging by using multiple microelectromechanical scanning mirrors.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] Confocal X-ray fluorescence imaging is a newer technique that allows control over depth, in addition to horizontal and vertical aiming, for example, when analyzing buried layers in a painting.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] CLSM is a scanning imaging technique in which the resolution obtained is best explained by comparing it with another scanning technique like that of the scanning electron microscope (SEM).
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] CLSM has the advantage of not requiring a probe to be suspended nanometers from the surface, as in an AFM or STM, for example, where the image is obtained by scanning with a fine tip over a surface.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] The distance from the objective lens to the surface (called the *working distance*) is typically comparable to that of a conventional optical microscope.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] It varies with the system optical design, but working distances from hundreds of micrometres to several millimeters are typical.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] In CLSM a specimen is illuminated by a point laser source, and each volume element is associated with a discrete scattering or fluorescence intensity.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] Here, the size of the scanning volume is determined by the spot size (close to diffraction limit) of the optical system because the image of the scanning laser is not an infinitely small point but a three-dimensional diffraction pattern.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] The size of this diffraction pattern and the focal volume it defines is controlled by the numerical aperture of the system's objective lens and the wavelength of the laser used.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] This can be seen as the classical resolution limit of conventional optical microscopes using wide-field illumination.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] However, with confocal microscopy it is even possible to improve on the resolution limit of wide-field illumination techniques because the confocal aperture can be closed down to eliminate higher orders of the diffraction pattern.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] For example, if the pinhole diameter is set to 1 Airy unit then only the first order of the diffraction pattern makes it through the aperture to the detector while the higher orders are blocked, thus improving resolution at the cost of a slight decrease in brightness.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] In fluorescence observations, the resolution limit of confocal microscopy is often limited by the signal-to-noise ratio caused by the small number of photons typically available in fluorescence microscopy.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] One can compensate for this effect by using more sensitive photodetectors or by increasing the intensity of the illuminating laser point source.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] Increasing the intensity of illumination laser risks excessive bleaching or other damage to the specimen of interest, especially for experiments in which comparison of fluorescence brightness is required.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] When imaging tissues that are differentially refractive, such as the spongy mesophyll of plant leaves or other air-space containing tissues, spherical aberrations that impair confocal image quality are often pronounced.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] Such aberrations however, can be significantly reduced by mounting samples in optically transparent, non-toxic perfluorocarbons such as perfluorodecalin, which readily infiltrates tissues and has a refractive index almost identical to that of water.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] When imaging in a reflection geometry, it is also possible to detect the interference of the reflected and scattered light of an object like an intracellular organelle.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] The interferometric nature of the signal allows to reduce the pinhole diameter down to 0.2 Airy units and therefore enables an ideal resolution enhancement of √2 without sacrificing the signal-to-noise ratio as in confocal fluorescence microscopy.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] CLSM is widely used in various biological science disciplines, from cell biology and genetics to microbiology and developmental biology.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] It is also used in quantum optics and nano-crystal imaging and spectroscopy.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] Clinically, CLSM is used in the evaluation of various eye diseases, and is particularly useful for imaging, qualitative analysis, and quantification of endothelial cells of the cornea.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] It is used for localizing and identifying the presence of filamentary fungal elements in the corneal stroma in cases of keratomycosis, enabling rapid diagnosis and thereby early institution of definitive therapy.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] Research into CLSM techniques for endoscopic procedures (endomicroscopy) is also showing promise.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] In the pharmaceutical industry, it was recommended to follow the manufacturing process of thin film pharmaceutical forms, to control the quality and uniformity of the drug distribution.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] Confocal microscopy is also used to study biofilms — complex porous structures that are the preferred habitat of microorganisms.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] Some of temporal and spatial function of biofilms can be understood only by studying their structure on micro- and meso-scales.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] The study of microscale is needed to detect the activity and organization of single microorganisms.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] CLSM is used as the data retrieval mechanism in some 3D optical data storage systems and has helped determine the age of the Magdalen papyrus.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] The IRENE system makes use of confocal microscopy for optical scanning and recovery of damaged historical audio.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] Wax phonograph cylinders inherently degrade due to contact with the stylus when replayed as intended; microscopy is non-contact, and often gives better sound than stylus playback.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] Laser scanning confocal microscopes are used in the characterization of the surface of microstructured materials, such as Silicon wafers used in solar cell production.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] During the first processing steps, wafers are wet-chemically etched with acid or alkaline compounds, rendering a texture to their surface.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] Laser confocal microscopy is then used to observe the state of the resulting surface at the micrometer lever.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] Laser confocal microscopy can also be used to analyze the thickness and height of metallization fingers printed on top of solar cells.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] The point spread function of the pinhole is an ellipsoid, several times as long as it is wide.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] This limits the axial resolution of the microscope.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] One technique of overcoming this is 4Pi microscopy where incident and or emitted light are allowed to interfere from both above and below the sample to reduce the volume of the ellipsoid.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] An alternative technique is **confocal theta microscopy**.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] In this technique the cone of illuminating light and detected light are at an angle to each other (best results when they are perpendicular).
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] The intersection of the two point spread functions gives a much smaller effective sample volume.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] From this evolved the single plane illumination microscope.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] Additionally deconvolution may be employed using an experimentally derived point spread function to remove the out of focus light, improving contrast in both the axial and lateral planes.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] There are confocal variants that achieve resolution below the diffraction limit such as stimulated emission depletion microscopy (STED).
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] Besides this technique a broad variety of other (not confocal based) super-resolution techniques are available like PALM, (d)STORM, SIM, and so on.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] They all have their own advantages such as ease of use, resolution, and the need for special equipment, buffers, or fluorophores.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] To image samples at low temperatures, two main approaches have been used, both based on the laser scanning confocal microscopy architecture.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] One approach is to use a continuous flow cryostat: only the sample is at low temperature and it is optically addressed through a transparent window.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] Another possible approach is to have part of the optics (especially the microscope objective) in a cryogenic storage dewar.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] This second approach, although more cumbersome, guarantees better mechanical stability and avoids the losses due to the window.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] To study molecular interactions using the CLSM Förster resonance energy transfer (FRET) can be used to confirm that two proteins are within a certain distance to one another.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] In 1940 Hans Goldmann, ophthalmologist in Bern, Switzerland, developed a slit lamp system to document eye examinations.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] This system is considered by some later authors as the first confocal optical system.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] In 1943 Zyun Koana published a confocal system.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] In 1951 Hiroto Naora, a colleague of Koana, described a confocal microscope in the journal Science for spectrophotometry.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] The first confocal *scanning* microscope was built by Marvin Minsky in 1955 and a patent was filed in 1957.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] The scanning of the illumination point in the focal plane was achieved by moving the stage.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] No scientific publication was submitted and no images made with it were preserved.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] In the 1960s, the Czechoslovak Mojmír Petráň from the Medical Faculty of the Charles University in Plzeň developed the Tandem-Scanning-Microscope, the first commercialized confocal microscope.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] It was sold by a small company in Czechoslovakia and in the United States by Tracor-Northern (later Noran) and used a rotating Nipkow disk to generate multiple excitation and emission pinholes.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] The Czechoslovak patent was filed 1966 by Petráň and Milan Hadravský, a Czechoslovak coworker.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] A first scientific publication with data and images generated with this microscope was published in the journal Science in 1967, authored by M.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] David Egger from Yale University and Petráň.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] As a footnote to this paper it is mentioned that Petráň designed the microscope and supervised its construction and that he was, in part, a "research associate" at Yale.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] A second publication from 1968 described the theory and the technical details of the instrument and had Hadravský and Robert Galambos, the head of the group at Yale, as additional authors.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] David Egger and Paul Davidovits from Yale University, published two papers describing the first confocal *laser* scanning microscope.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] It was a point scanner, meaning just one illumination spot was generated.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] It used epi-Illumination-reflection microscopy for the observation of nerve tissue.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] A 5 mW Helium-Neon-Laser with 633 nm light was reflected by a semi-transparent mirror towards the objective.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] The objective was a simple lens with a focal length of 8.5 mm.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] As opposed to all earlier and most later systems, the sample was scanned by movement of this lens (objective scanning), leading to a movement of the focal point.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] Reflected light came back to the semitransparent mirror, the transmitted part was focused by another lens on the detection pinhole behind which a photomultiplier tube was placed.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] The signal was visualized by a CRT of an oscilloscope, the cathode ray was moved simultaneously with the objective.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] A special device allowed to make Polaroid photos, three of which were shown in the 1971 publication.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] The authors speculate about fluorescent dyes for *in vivo* investigations.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] The motivation for their development was that in the Tandem-Scanning-Microscope only a fraction of 10−7 of the illumination light participates in generating the image in the eye piece.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] Thus, image quality was not sufficient for most biological investigations.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] Sheppard and Amarjyoti Choudhury, Oxford, UK, published a theoretical analysis of confocal and laser-scanning microscopes.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] It is probably the first publication using the term "confocal microscope".
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] In 1978, the brothers Christoph Cremer and Thomas Cremer published a design for a confocal laser-scanning-microscope using fluorescent excitation with electronic autofocus.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] They also suggested a laser point illumination by using a "4π-point-hologramme".
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] This CLSM design combined the laser scanning method with the 3D detection of biological objects labeled with fluorescent markers for the first time.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] In 1978 and 1980, the Oxford-group around Colin Sheppard and Tony Wilson described a confocal microscope with epi-laser-illumination, stage scanning and photomultiplier tubes as detectors.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] The stage could move along the optical axis (z-axis), allowing optical serial sections.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] In 1979 Fred Brakenhoff and coworkers demonstrated that the theoretical advantages of optical sectioning and resolution improvement are indeed achievable in practice.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] In 1985 this group became the first to publish convincing images taken on a confocal microscope that were able to answer biological questions.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] Shortly after many more groups started using confocal microscopy to answer scientific questions that until then had remained a mystery due to technological limitations.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] Sheppard from Oxford published the first work whereby a confocal microscope was controlled by a computer.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] The first commercial laser scanning microscope, the stage-scanner SOM-25 was offered by Oxford Optoelectronics (after several take-overs acquired by BioRad) starting in 1982.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] It was based on the design of the Oxford group.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] In the mid-1980s, William Bradshaw Amos and John Graham White and colleagues working at the Laboratory of Molecular Biology in Cambridge built the first confocal beam scanning microscope.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] The stage with the sample was not moving, instead the illumination spot was, allowing faster image acquisition: four images per second with 512 lines each.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] Hugely magnified intermediate images, due to a 1–2 meter long beam path, allowed the use of a conventional iris diaphragm as a 'pinhole', with diameters ~1 mm.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] First micrographs were taken with long-term exposure on film before a digital camera was added.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] A further improvement allowed zooming into the preparation for the first time.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] Zeiss, Leitz and Cambridge Instruments had no interest in a commercial production.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] The Medical Research Council (MRC) finally sponsored development of a prototype.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] The design was acquired by Bio-Rad, amended with computer control and commercialized as 'MRC 500'.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] The successor MRC 600 was later the basis for the development of the first two-photon-fluorescent microscope developed 1990 at Cornell University.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] Developments at the KTH Royal Institute of Technology in Stockholm around the same time led to a commercial CLSM distributed by the Swedish company Sarastro.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] The venture was acquired in 1990 by Molecular Dynamics, but the CLSM was eventually discontinued.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] In Germany, Heidelberg Instruments, founded in 1984, developed a CLSM, which was initially meant for industrial applications rather than biology.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] This instrument was taken over in 1990 by Leica Lasertechnik.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] Zeiss already had a non-confocal flying-spot laser scanning microscope on the market which was upgraded to a confocal.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] A report from 1990, mentioned some manufacturers of confocals: Sarastro, Technical Instrument, Meridian Instruments, Bio-Rad, Leica, Tracor-Northern and Zeiss.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] In 1989, Fritz Karl Preikschat, with his son Ekhard Preikschat, invented the scanning laser diode microscope for particle-size analysis. and co-founded Lasentec to commercialize it.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] In 2001, Lasentec was acquired by Mettler Toledo.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] They are used mostly in the pharmaceutical industry to provide in-situ control of the crystallization process in large purification systems.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] In standard confocal instruments, the second or "output" pinhole is utilized to filter out the emitted or scattered light.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] Traditionally, this pinhole is a passive component that blocks light to filter the illumination optically.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] However, newer designs have tried to perform this filtering digitally.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] Recent approaches have replaced the passive pinhole with a compound detector element.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] Typically, after digital processing, this approach leads to better resolution and photon budget, as the resolution limit can approach that of an infinitely small pinhole.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/confocal-microscopy] Other researchers have attempted to digitally refocus the light from a point excitation source using deep convolutional neural networks.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] A **molecular vibration** is a periodic motion of the atoms of a molecule relative to each other, such that the center of mass of the molecule remains unchanged.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] The typical **vibrational frequencies** range from less than 1013 Hz to approximately 1014 Hz, corresponding to wavenumbers of approximately 300 to 3000 cm−1 and wavelengths of approximately 30 to 3 μm.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] Vibrations of polyatomic molecules are described in terms of normal modes, which are independent of each other, but each normal mode involves simultaneous vibrations of parts of the molecule.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] In general, a non-linear molecule with *N* atoms has 3*N* − 6 normal modes of vibration, but a *linear* molecule has 3*N* − 5 modes, because rotation about the molecular axis cannot be observed.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] A diatomic molecule has one normal mode of vibration, since it can only stretch or compress the single bond.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] A molecular vibration is excited when the molecule absorbs energy, Δ*E*, corresponding to the vibration's frequency, *ν*, according to the relation Δ*E* = *hν*, where *h* is the Planck constant.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] A fundamental vibration is evoked when one such quantum of energy is absorbed by the molecule in its ground state.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] When multiple quanta are absorbed, the first and possibly higher overtones are excited.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] To a first approximation, the motion in a normal vibration can be described as a kind of simple harmonic motion.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] In this approximation, the vibrational energy is a quadratic function (parabola) with respect to the atomic displacements and the first overtone has twice the frequency of the fundamental.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] In reality, vibrations are anharmonic and the first overtone has a frequency that is slightly lower than twice that of the fundamental.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] Excitation of the higher overtones involves progressively less and less additional energy and eventually leads to dissociation of the molecule, because the potential energy of the molecule is more like a Morse potential or more accurately, a Morse/Long-range potential.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] The vibrational states of a molecule can be probed in a variety of ways.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] The most direct way is through infrared spectroscopy, as vibrational transitions typically require an amount of energy that corresponds to the infrared region of the spectrum.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] Raman spectroscopy, which typically uses visible light, can also be used to measure vibration frequencies directly.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] The two techniques are complementary and comparison between the two can provide useful structural information such as in the case of the rule of mutual exclusion for centrosymmetric molecules.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] Vibrational excitation can occur in conjunction with electronic excitation in the ultraviolet-visible region.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] The combined excitation is known as a vibronic transition, giving vibrational fine structure to electronic transitions, particularly for molecules in the gas state.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] Simultaneous excitation of a vibration and rotations gives rise to vibration–rotation spectra.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] For a molecule with N atoms, the positions of all N nuclei depend on a total of 3N coordinates, so that the molecule has 3N degrees of freedom including translation, rotation and vibration.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] Translation corresponds to movement of the center of mass whose position can be described by 3 cartesian coordinates.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] A nonlinear molecule can rotate about any of three mutually perpendicular axes and therefore has 3 rotational degrees of freedom.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] For a linear molecule, rotation about the molecular axis does not involve movement of any atomic nucleus, so there are only 2 rotational degrees of freedom which can vary the atomic coordinates.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] An equivalent argument is that the rotation of a linear molecule changes the direction of the molecular axis in space, which can be described by 2 coordinates corresponding to latitude and longitude.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] For a nonlinear molecule, the direction of one axis is described by these two coordinates, and the orientation of the molecule about this axis provides a third rotational coordinate.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] The number of vibrational modes is therefore 3N minus the number of translational and rotational degrees of freedom, or 3N − 5 for linear and 3N − 6 for nonlinear molecules.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] The coordinate of a normal vibration is a combination of *changes* in the positions of atoms in the molecule.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] When the vibration is excited the coordinate changes sinusoidally with a frequency ν, the frequency of the vibration.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] In a rocking, wagging or twisting coordinate the bond lengths within the groups involved do not change.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] Rocking is distinguished from wagging by the fact that the atoms in the group stay in the same plane.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] In ethylene there are 12 internal coordinates: 4 C–H stretching, 1 C–C stretching, 2 H–C–H bending, 2 CH2 rocking, 2 CH2 wagging, 1 twisting.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] Note that the H–C–C angles cannot be used as internal coordinates as well as the H–C–H angle because the angles at each carbon atom cannot all increase at the same time.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] Note that these coordinates do not correspond to normal modes (see *§ Normal coordinates*).
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] In other words, they do not correspond to particular frequencies or vibrational transitions.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] Within the CH2 group, commonly found in organic compounds, the two low mass hydrogens can vibrate in six different ways which can be grouped as 3 pairs of modes: 1.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] **symmetric** and **asymmetric stretching**, 2.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] (These figures do not represent the "recoil" of the C atoms, which, though necessarily present to balance the overall movements of the molecule, are much smaller than the movements of the lighter H atoms).
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] Symmetry–adapted coordinates may be created by applying a projection operator to a set of internal coordinates.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] The projection operator is constructed with the aid of the character table of the molecular point group.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] Illustrations of symmetry–adapted coordinates for most small molecules can be found in Nakamoto.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] The normal coordinates, denoted as *Q*, refer to the positions of atoms away from their equilibrium positions, with respect to a normal mode of vibration.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] Each normal mode is assigned a single normal coordinate, and so the normal coordinate refers to the "progress" along that normal mode at any given time.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] Formally, normal modes are determined by solving a secular determinant, and then the normal coordinates (over the normal modes) can be expressed as a summation over the cartesian coordinates (over the atom positions).
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] The normal modes diagonalize the matrix governing the molecular vibrations, so that each normal mode is an independent molecular vibration.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] If the molecule possesses symmetries, the normal modes "transform as" an irreducible representation under its point group.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] The normal modes are determined by applying group theory, and projecting the irreducible representation onto the cartesian coordinates.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] When two or more normal coordinates belong to the same irreducible representation of the molecular point group (colloquially, have the same symmetry) there is "mixing" and the coefficients of the combination cannot be determined *a priori*.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] The coefficients a and b are found by performing a full normal coordinate analysis by means of the Wilson GF method.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] Perhaps surprisingly, molecular vibrations can be treated using Newtonian mechanics to calculate the correct vibration frequencies.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] The basic assumption is that each vibration can be treated as though it corresponds to a spring.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] In the harmonic approximation the spring obeys Hooke's law: the force required to extend the spring is proportional to the extension.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] The proportionality constant is known as a *force constant, k*.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] It remains to define the reduced mass, *μ*.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] In general, the reduced mass of a diatomic molecule, AB, is expressed in terms of the atomic masses, *mA* and *mB*, as ${\frac {1}{\mu }}={\frac {1}{m_{A}}}+{\frac {1}{m_{B}}}.$ The use of the reduced mass ensures that the centre of mass of the molecule is not affected by the vibration.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] In the harmonic approximation the potential energy of the molecule is a quadratic function of the normal coordinate.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] When two or more normal vibrations have the same symmetry a full normal coordinate analysis must be performed (see GF method).
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] The vibration frequencies, *ν**i*, are obtained from the eigenvalues, *λ**i*, of the matrix product ***GF***.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] ***G*** is a matrix of numbers derived from the masses of the atoms and the geometry of the molecule.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] ***F*** is a matrix derived from force-constant values.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] Details concerning the determination of the eigenvalues can be found in.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] In the harmonic approximation the potential energy is a quadratic function of the normal coordinates.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] Solving the Schrödinger wave equation, the energy states for each normal coordinate are given by $E_{n}=h\left(n+{1 \over 2}\right)\nu =h\left(n+{1 \over 2}\right){1 \over {2\pi }}{\sqrt {k \over m}},$ where *n* is a quantum number that can take values of 0, 1, 2, ...
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] In molecular spectroscopy where several types of molecular energy are studied and several quantum numbers are used, this *vibrational quantum number* is often designated as *v*.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] The difference in energy when *n* (or *v*) changes by 1 is therefore equal to $h\nu$ , the product of the Planck constant and the vibration frequency derived using classical mechanics.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] For a transition from level *n* to level *n+1* due to absorption of a photon, the frequency of the photon is equal to the classical vibration frequency $\nu$ (in the harmonic oscillator approximation).
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] See quantum harmonic oscillator for graphs of the first 5 wave functions, which allow certain selection rules to be formulated.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] For example, for a harmonic oscillator transitions are allowed only when the quantum number *n* changes by one, $\Delta n=\pm 1$ but this does not apply to an anharmonic oscillator; the observation of overtones is only possible because vibrations are anharmonic.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] Another consequence of anharmonicity is that transitions such as between states *n* = 2 and *n* = 1 have slightly less energy than transitions between the ground state and first excited state.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] Such a transition gives rise to a hot band.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] To describe vibrational levels of an anharmonic oscillator, Dunham expansion is used.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] When it comes to polyatomic molecules, it is common to solve the Schrödinger Equation using Watson's nuclear motion Hamiltonian.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] Similar as for diatomics, this can be done within the harmonic approximation as stated above.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] For the anharmonic calculation of vibrational spectra of polyatomic molecules, more sophisticated approaches are used.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] Prominent examples in computational chemistry are 2nd order vibrational perturbation theory (VPT2) or vibrational configuration interaction theory (VCI).
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] In an infrared spectrum the intensity of an absorption band is proportional to the derivative of the molecular dipole moment with respect to the normal coordinate.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] Likewise, the intensity of Raman bands depends on the derivative of polarizability with respect to the normal coordinate.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] There is also a dependence on the fourth-power of the wavelength of the laser used.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] In chemistry and physics, **Raman scattering** or the **Raman effect** (/ˈrɑːmən/) is the inelastic scattering of photons by matter, meaning that there is both an exchange of energy and a change in the light's direction.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] Typically this effect involves vibrational energy being gained by a molecule as incident photons from a visible laser are shifted to lower energy.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] This is called *normal Stokes-Raman scattering*.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] Light has a certain probability of being scattered by a material.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] When photons are scattered, most of them are elastically scattered (Rayleigh scattering), such that the scattered photons have the same energy (frequency, wavelength, and therefore color) as the incident photons, but different direction.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] Rayleigh scattering usually has an intensity in the range 0.1% to 0.01% relative to that of a radiation source.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] An even smaller fraction of the scattered photons (about 1 in a million) can be scattered *inelastically*, with the scattered photons having an energy different (usually lower) from those of the incident photons—these are Raman scattered photons.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] Because of conservation of energy, the material either gains or loses energy in the process.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] The effect is exploited by chemists and physicists to gain information about materials for a variety of purposes by performing various forms of Raman spectroscopy.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] Many other variants of Raman spectroscopy allow rotational energy to be examined, if gas samples are used, and electronic energy levels may be examined if an X-ray source is used, in addition to other possibilities.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] More complex techniques involving pulsed lasers, multiple laser beams and so on are known.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] The Raman effect is named after Indian scientist C.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] Raman, who discovered it in 1928 with assistance from his student K.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] Raman was awarded the 1930 Nobel Prize in Physics for his discovery of Raman scattering.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] The elastic light scattering phenomena called Rayleigh scattering, in which light retains its energy, was described in the 19th century.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] The intensity of Rayleigh scattering is about 10−3 to 10−4 compared to the intensity of the exciting source.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] In 1908, another form of elastic scattering, called Mie scattering was discovered.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] The inelastic scattering of light was predicted by Adolf Smekal in 1923 and in older German-language literature it has been referred to as the Smekal-Raman-Effekt.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] Raman published his work on the "Molecular Diffraction of Light", the first of a series of investigations with his collaborators that ultimately led to his discovery (on 16 February 1928) of the radiation effect that bears his name.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] The Raman effect was first reported by Raman and his coworker K.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] Krishnan, and independently by Grigory Landsberg and Leonid Mandelstam, in Moscow on 21 February 1928 (5 days after Raman and Krishnan).
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] In the former Soviet Union, Raman's contribution was always disputed; thus in Russian scientific literature the effect is usually referred to as "combination scattering" or "combinatory scattering".
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] Raman received the Nobel Prize in 1930 for his work on the scattering of light.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] In 1998 the Raman effect was designated a National Historic Chemical Landmark by the American Chemical Society in recognition of its significance as a tool for analyzing the composition of liquids, gases, and solids.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] Modern Raman spectroscopy nearly always involves the use of lasers as an exciting light source.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] Because lasers were not available until more than three decades after the discovery of the effect, Raman and Krishnan used a mercury lamp and photographic plates to record spectra.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] Early spectra took hours or even days to acquire due to weak light sources, poor sensitivity of the detectors and the weak Raman scattering cross-sections of most materials.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] The most common modern detectors are charge-coupled devices (CCDs).
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] Photodiode arrays and photomultiplier tubes were common prior to the adoption of CCDs.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] The following focuses on the theory of normal (non-resonant, spontaneous, vibrational) Raman scattering of light by discrete molecules.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] X-ray Raman spectroscopy is conceptually similar but involves excitation of electronic, rather than vibrational, energy levels.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] Raman scattering generally gives information about vibrations within a molecule.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] In the case of gases, information about rotational energy can also be gleaned.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] For solids, phonon modes may also be observed.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] The basics of infrared absorption regarding molecular vibrations apply to Raman scattering although the selection rules are different.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] For any given molecule, there are a total of 3N degrees of freedom, where N is the number of atoms.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] This number arises from the ability of each atom in a molecule to move in three dimensions.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] When dealing with molecules, it is more common to consider the movement of the molecule as a whole.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] Consequently, the 3N degrees of freedom are partitioned into molecular translational, rotational, and vibrational motion.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] Three of the degrees of freedom correspond to translational motion of the molecule as a whole (along each of the three spatial dimensions).
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] Similarly, three degrees of freedom correspond to rotations of the molecule about the x , y , and z -axes.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] Linear molecules only have two rotations because rotations along the bond axis do not change the positions of the atoms in the molecule.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] The remaining degrees of freedom correspond to molecular vibrational modes.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] These modes include stretching and bending motions of the chemical bonds of the molecule.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] For a linear molecule, the number of vibrational modes is 3N-5, whereas for a non-linear molecule the number of vibrational modes is 3N-6.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] Molecular vibrational energy is known to be quantized and can be modeled using the quantum harmonic oscillator (QHO) approximation or a Dunham expansion when anharmonicity is important.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] The energy range for vibrations is in the range of approximately 5 to 3500 cm−1.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] The fraction of molecules occupying a given vibrational mode at a given temperature follows a Boltzmann distribution.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] A molecule can be excited to a higher vibrational mode through the direct absorption of a photon of the appropriate energy, which falls in the terahertz or infrared range.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] This forms the basis of infrared spectroscopy.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] Alternatively, the same vibrational excitation can be produced by an inelastic scattering process.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] This is called Stokes Raman scattering, by analogy with the Stokes shift in fluorescence discovered by George Stokes in 1852, with light emission at longer wavelength (now known to correspond to lower energy) than the absorbed incident light.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] Conceptually similar effects can be caused by neutrons or electrons rather than light.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] An increase in photon energy which leaves the molecule in a lower vibrational energy state is called anti-Stokes scattering.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] Raman scattering is conceptualized as involving a virtual electronic energy level which corresponds to the energy of the exciting laser photons.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] Absorption of a photon excites the molecule to the imaginary state and re-emission leads to Raman or Rayleigh scattering.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] In all three cases the final state has the same electronic energy as the initial state but is higher in vibrational energy in the case of Stokes Raman scattering, lower in the case of anti-Stokes Raman scattering or the same in the case of Rayleigh scattering.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] Normally this is thought of in terms of wavenumbers, where ${\tilde {\nu }}_{0}$ is the wavenumber of the laser and ${\tilde {\nu }}_{M}$ is the wavenumber of the vibrational transition.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] When the exciting laser energy corresponds to an actual electronic excitation of the molecule then the resonance Raman effect occurs.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] A classical physics based model is able to account for Raman scattering and predicts an increase in the intensity which scales with the fourth-power of the light frequency.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] Light scattering by a molecule is associated with oscillations of an induced electric dipole.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] The oscillating electric field component of electromagnetic radiation may bring about an induced dipole in a molecule which follows the alternating electric field which is modulated by the molecular vibrations.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] Oscillations at the external field frequency are therefore observed along with beat frequencies resulting from the external field and normal mode vibrations.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] The spectrum of the scattered photons is termed the Raman spectrum.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] It shows the intensity of the scattered light as a function of its frequency difference *Δν* to the incident photons, more commonly called a Raman shift.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] The locations of corresponding Stokes and anti-Stokes peaks form a symmetric pattern around the Rayleigh*Δν=0* line.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] The frequency shifts are symmetric because they correspond to the energy difference between the same upper and lower resonant states.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] The intensities of the pairs of features will typically differ, though.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] They depend on the populations of the initial states of the material, which in turn depend on the temperature.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] In thermodynamic equilibrium, the lower state will be more populated than the upper state.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] Therefore, the rate of transitions from the more populated lower state to the upper state (Stokes transitions) will be higher than in the opposite direction (anti-Stokes transitions).
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] Correspondingly, Stokes scattering peaks are stronger than anti-Stokes scattering peaks.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] In contrast to IR spectroscopy, where there is a requirement for a change in dipole moment for vibrational excitation to take place, Raman scattering requires a change in polarizability.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] A Raman transition from one state to another is allowed only if the molecular polarizability of those states is different.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] For a vibration, this means that the derivative of the polarizability with respect to the normal coordinate associated to the vibration is non-zero: ${\frac {\partial \alpha }{\partial Q}}\neq 0$ .
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] In general, a normal mode is Raman active if it transforms with the same symmetry of the quadratic forms $(x^{2},y^{2},z^{2},xy,xz,yz)$ , which can be verified from the character table of the molecule's point group.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] As with IR spectroscopy, only fundamental excitations ( $\Delta \nu =\pm 1$ ) are allowed according to the QHO.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] There are however many cases where overtones are observed.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] The rule of mutual exclusion, which states that vibrational modes cannot be both IR and Raman active, applies to certain molecules.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] The specific selection rules state that the allowed rotational transitions are $\Delta J=\pm 2$ , where J is the rotational state.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] This generally is only relevant to molecules in the gas phase where the Raman linewidths are small enough for rotational transitions to be resolved.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] A selection rule relevant only to ordered solid materials states that only phonons with zero phase angle can be observed by IR and Raman, except when phonon confinement is manifest.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] Monitoring the polarization of the scattered photons is useful for understanding the connections between molecular symmetry and Raman activity which may assist in assigning peaks in Raman spectra.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] Light polarized in a single direction only gives access to some Raman–active modes, but rotating the polarization gives access to other modes.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] Each mode is separated according to its symmetry.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] When polarized light interacts with a molecule, it distorts the molecule which induces an equal and opposite effect in the plane-wave, causing it to be rotated by the difference between the orientation of the molecule and the angle of polarization of the light wave.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] If $\rho \geq {\frac {3}{4}}$ , then the vibrations at that frequency are *depolarized*; meaning they are not totally symmetric.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] The Raman-scattering process as described above takes place spontaneously; i.e., in random time intervals, one of the many incoming photons is scattered by the material.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] This process is thus called *spontaneous Raman scattering*.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] In that case, the total Raman-scattering rate is increased beyond that of spontaneous Raman scattering: pump photons are converted more rapidly into additional Stokes photons.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] The more Stokes photons that are already present, the faster more of them are added.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] Effectively, this *amplifies* the Stokes light in the presence of the pump light, which is exploited in Raman amplifiers and Raman lasers.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] Stimulated Raman scattering is a nonlinear optical effect.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] Suppose that the distance between two points A and B of an exciting beam is *x*.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] Generally, as the exciting frequency is not equal to the scattered Raman frequency, the corresponding relative wavelengths λ and λ' are not equal.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] For Θ = *π*, the scattered amplitudes are opposite, so that the Raman scattered beam remains weak.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] In labs, femtosecond laser pulses must be used because the ISRS becomes very weak if the pulses are too long.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] Thus ISRS cannot be observed using nanosecond pulses making ordinary time-incoherent light.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] The inverse Raman effect is a form of Raman scattering first noted by W.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] In some circumstances, Stokes scattering can exceed anti-Stokes scattering; in these cases the continuum (on leaving the material) is observed to have an absorption line (a dip in intensity) at ν*L*+ν*M*.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] This phenomenon is referred to as the *inverse Raman effect*; the application of the phenomenon is referred to as *inverse Raman spectroscopy*, and a record of the continuum is referred to as an *inverse Raman spectrum*.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] In the original description of the inverse Raman effect, the authors discuss both absorption from a continuum of higher frequencies and absorption from a continuum of lower frequencies.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] They note that absorption from a continuum of lower frequencies will not be observed if the Raman frequency of the material is vibrational in origin and if the material is in thermal equilibrium.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] For high-intensity continuous wave (CW) lasers, stimulated Raman scattering can be used to produce a broad bandwidth supercontinuum.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] This process can also be seen as a special case of four-wave mixing, in which the frequencies of the two incident photons are equal and the emitted spectra are found in two bands separated from the incident light by the phonon energies.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] The initial Raman spectrum is built up with spontaneous emission and is amplified later on.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] At high pumping levels in long fibers, higher-order Raman spectra can be generated by using the Raman spectrum as a new starting point, thereby building a chain of new spectra with decreasing amplitude.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] The disadvantage of intrinsic noise due to the initial spontaneous process can be overcome by seeding a spectrum at the beginning, or even using a feedback loop as in a resonator to stabilize the process.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] Since this technology easily fits into the fast evolving fiber laser field and there is demand for transversal coherent high-intensity light sources (i.e., broadband telecommunication, imaging applications), Raman amplification and spectrum generation might be widely used in the near-future.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] Raman spectroscopy employs the Raman effect for substances analysis.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] The spectrum of the Raman-scattered light depends on the molecular constituents present and their state, allowing the spectrum to be used for material identification and analysis.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] Raman spectroscopy is used to analyze a wide range of materials, including gases, liquids, and solids.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] Highly complex materials such as biological organisms and human tissue can also be analyzed by Raman spectroscopy.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] For solid materials, Raman scattering is used as a tool to detect high-frequency phonon and magnon excitations.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] Raman lidar is used in atmospheric physics to measure the atmospheric extinction coefficient and the water vapour vertical distribution.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] Due to its velocity-selective nature, the stimulated Raman transition is useful for cooling atoms.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] It also enables the construction of atom interferometer by providing a well-defined momentum kick.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] Stimulated Raman transitions are also widely used for manipulating a trapped ion's energy levels, and thus basis qubit states.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] Raman spectroscopy can be used to determine the force constant and bond length for molecules that do not have an infrared absorption spectrum.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] Raman amplification is used in optical amplifiers.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] The Raman effect is also involved in producing the appearance of the blue sky (see Rayleigh Scattering: 'Rayleigh scattering of molecular nitrogen and oxygen in the atmosphere includes elastic scattering as well as the inelastic contribution from rotational Raman scattering in air').
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-scattering] Raman spectroscopy has been used to chemically image small molecules, such as nucleic acids, in biological systems by a vibrational tag.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Raman spectroscopy relies upon inelastic scattering of photons, known as Raman scattering.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] A source of monochromatic light, usually from a laser in the visible, near infrared, or near ultraviolet range is used, although X-rays can also be used.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The laser light interacts with molecular vibrations, phonons or other excitations in the system, resulting in the energy of the laser photons being shifted up or down.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The shift in energy gives information about the vibrational modes in the system.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Time-resolved spectroscopy and infrared spectroscopy typically yield similar yet complementary information.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Typically, a sample is illuminated with a laser beam.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Electromagnetic radiation from the illuminated spot is collected with a lens.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Elastic scattered radiation at the wavelength corresponding to the laser line (Rayleigh scattering) is filtered out by either a notch filter, edge pass filter, or a band pass filter, while the rest of the collected light is dispersed onto a detector.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Spontaneous Raman scattering is typically very weak.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] As a result, for many years the main difficulty in collecting Raman spectra was separating the weak inelastically scattered light from the intense Rayleigh scattered laser light (referred to as "laser rejection").
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Historically, Raman spectrometers used holographic gratings and multiple dispersion stages to achieve a high degree of laser rejection.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] In the past, photomultipliers were the detectors of choice for dispersive Raman setups, which resulted in long acquisition times.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] However, modern instrumentation almost universally employs notch or edge filters for laser rejection.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Dispersive single-stage spectrographs (axial transmissive (AT) or Czerny–Turner (CT) monochromators) paired with CCD detectors are most common although Fourier transform (FT) spectrometers are also common for use with NIR lasers.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The name "Raman spectroscopy" typically refers to vibrational Raman spectroscopy using laser wavelengths which are not absorbed by the sample.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] There are many other variations of Raman spectroscopy including surface-enhanced Raman, resonance Raman, tip-enhanced Raman, polarized Raman, stimulated Raman, transmission Raman, spatially-offset Raman, and hyper Raman.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Although the inelastic scattering of light was predicted by Adolf Smekal in 1923, it was not observed in practice until 1928.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The Raman effect was named after one of its discoverers, the Indian scientist C.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Raman, who observed the effect in organic liquids in 1928 together with K.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Krishnan, and independently by Grigory Landsberg and Leonid Mandelstam in inorganic crystals.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Raman won the Nobel Prize in Physics in 1930 for this discovery.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The first observation of Raman spectra in gases was in 1929 by Franco Rasetti.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Systematic pioneering theory of the Raman effect was developed by Czechoslovak physicist George Placzek between 1930 and 1934.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The mercury arc became the principal light source, first with photographic detection and then with spectrophotometric detection.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] In the years following its discovery, Raman spectroscopy was used to provide the first catalog of molecular vibrational frequencies.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Typically, the sample was held in a long tube and illuminated along its length with a beam of filtered monochromatic light generated by a gas discharge lamp.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The photons that were scattered by the sample were collected through an optical flat at the end of the tube.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] To maximize the sensitivity, the sample was highly concentrated (1 M or more) and relatively large volumes (5 mL or more) were used.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The magnitude of the Raman effect correlates with the polarizability of the electrons in a molecule.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] It is a form of inelastic light scattering, where a photon excites the sample.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] This excitation puts the molecule into a virtual energy state for a short time before the photon is emitted.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Inelastic scattering means that the energy of the emitted photon is of either lower or higher energy than the incident photon.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] After the scattering event, the sample is in a different rotational or vibrational state.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] For the total energy of the system to remain constant after the molecule moves to a new rovibronic (rotational–vibrational–electronic) state, the scattered photon shifts to a different energy, and therefore a different frequency.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] This energy difference is equal to that between the initial and final rovibronic states of the molecule.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] If the final state is higher in energy than the initial state, the scattered photon will be shifted to a lower frequency (lower energy) so that the total energy remains the same.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] This shift in frequency is called a Stokes shift, or downshift.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] If the final state is lower in energy, the scattered photon will be shifted to a higher frequency, which is called an anti-Stokes shift, or upshift.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] For a molecule to exhibit a Raman effect, there must be a change in its electric dipole-electric dipole polarizability with respect to the vibrational coordinate corresponding to the rovibronic state.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The intensity of the Raman scattering is proportional to this polarizability change.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Therefore, the Raman spectrum (scattering intensity as a function of the frequency shifts) depends on the rovibronic states of the molecule.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The Raman effect is based on the interaction between the electron cloud of a sample and the external electric field of the monochromatic light, which can create an induced dipole moment within the molecule based on its polarizability.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Because the laser light does not excite the molecule there can be no real transition between energy levels.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The Raman effect should not be confused with emission (fluorescence or phosphorescence), where a molecule in an excited electronic state emits a photon and returns to the ground electronic state, in many cases to a vibrationally excited state on the ground electronic state potential energy surface.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Raman scattering also contrasts with infrared (IR) absorption, where the energy of the absorbed photon matches the difference in energy between the initial and final rovibronic states.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The dependence of Raman on the electric dipole-electric dipole polarizability derivative also differs from IR spectroscopy, which depends on the electric dipole moment derivative, the atomic polar tensor (APT).
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] This contrasting feature allows rovibronic transitions that might not be active in IR to be analyzed using Raman spectroscopy, as exemplified by the rule of mutual exclusion in centrosymmetric molecules.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Transitions which have large Raman intensities often have weak IR intensities and vice versa.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] If a bond is strongly polarized, a small change in its length such as that which occurs during a vibration has only a small resultant effect on polarization.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] C-O, N-O, O-H) are therefore, comparatively weak Raman scatterers.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Such polarized bonds, however, carry their electrical charges during the vibrational motion, (unless neutralized by symmetry factors), and this results in a larger net dipole moment change during the vibration, producing a strong IR absorption band.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Conversely, relatively neutral bonds (e.g.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] C-C, C-H, C=C) suffer large changes in polarizability during a vibration.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] However, the dipole moment is not similarly affected such that while vibrations involving predominantly this type of bond are strong Raman scatterers, they are weak in the IR.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] A third vibrational spectroscopy technique, inelastic incoherent neutron scattering (IINS), can be used to determine the frequencies of vibrations in highly symmetric molecules that may be both IR and Raman inactive.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The IINS selection rules, or allowed transitions, differ from those of IR and Raman, so the three techniques are complementary.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] They all give the same frequency for a given vibrational transition, but the relative intensities provide different information due to the different types of interaction between the molecule and the incoming particles, photons for IR and Raman, and neutrons for IINS.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Raman shifts are typically reported in wavenumbers, which have units of inverse length, as this value is directly related to energy.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] where Δν̃ is the Raman shift expressed in wavenumber, λ0 is the excitation wavelength, and λ1 is the Raman spectrum wavelength.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Most commonly, the unit chosen for expressing wavenumber in Raman spectra is inverse centimeters (cm−1).
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Modern Raman spectroscopy nearly always involves the use of lasers as excitation light sources.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Various colored filters and chemical solutions were used to select certain wavelength regions for excitation and detection but the photographic spectra were still dominated by a broad center line corresponding to Rayleigh scattering of the excitation source.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Technological advances have made Raman spectroscopy much more sensitive, particularly since the 1980s.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The most common modern detectors are now charge-coupled devices (CCDs).
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The advent of reliable, stable, inexpensive lasers with narrow bandwidths has also had an impact.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Raman spectroscopy requires a light source such as a laser.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The resolution of the spectrum relies on the bandwidth of the laser source used.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Generally shorter wavelength lasers give stronger Raman scattering due to the ν4 increase in Raman scattering cross-sections, but issues with sample degradation or fluorescence may result.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Continuous wave lasers are most common for normal Raman spectroscopy, but pulsed lasers may also be used.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] These often have wider bandwidths than their CW counterparts but are very useful for other forms of Raman spectroscopy such as transient, time-resolved and resonance Raman.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Raman scattered light is typically collected and either dispersed by a spectrograph or used with an interferometer for detection by Fourier Transform (FT) methods.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] In many cases commercially available FT-IR spectrometers can be modified to become FT-Raman spectrometers.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] In most cases, modern Raman spectrometers use array detectors such as CCDs.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Various types of CCDs exist which are optimized for different wavelength ranges.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Intensified CCDs can be used for very weak signals and/or pulsed lasers.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The spectral range depends on the size of the CCD and the focal length of spectrograph used.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] It was once common to use monochromators coupled to photomultiplier tubes.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] In this case the monochromator would need to be moved in order to scan through a spectral range.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] FT–Raman is almost always used with NIR lasers and appropriate detectors must be used depending on the exciting wavelength.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Germanium or Indium gallium arsenide (InGaAs) detectors are commonly used.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] It is usually necessary to separate the Raman scattered light from the Rayleigh signal and reflected laser signal in order to collect high quality Raman spectra using a laser rejection filter.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Notch or long-pass optical filters are typically used for this purpose.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Before the advent of holographic filters it was common to use a triple-grating monochromator in subtractive mode to isolate the desired signal.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] This may still be used to record very small Raman shifts as holographic filters typically reflect some of the low frequency bands in addition to the unshifted laser light.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] However, Volume hologram filters are becoming more common which allow shifts as low as 5 cm−1 to be observed.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Raman spectroscopy is used in chemistry to identify molecules and study chemical bonding and intramolecular bonds.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Because vibrational frequencies are specific to a molecule's chemical bonds and symmetry (the fingerprint region of organic molecules is in the wavenumber range 500–1,500 cm−1), Raman provides a fingerprint to identify molecules.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] For instance, Raman and IR spectra were used to determine the vibrational frequencies of SiO, Si2O2, and Si3O3 on the basis of normal coordinate analyses.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Raman is also used to study the addition of a substrate to an enzyme.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] In solid-state physics, Raman spectroscopy is used to characterize materials, measure temperature, and find the crystallographic orientation of a sample.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] As with single molecules, a solid material can be identified by characteristic phonon modes.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Information on the population of a phonon mode is given by the ratio of the Stokes and anti-Stokes intensity of the spontaneous Raman signal.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Raman spectroscopy can also be used to observe other low frequency excitations of a solid, such as plasmons, magnons, and superconducting gap excitations.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Distributed temperature sensing (DTS) uses the Raman-shifted backscatter from laser pulses to determine the temperature along optical fibers.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The orientation of an anisotropic crystal can be found from the polarization of Raman-scattered light with respect to the crystal and the polarization of the laser light, if the crystal structure's point group is known.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] In nanotechnology, a Raman microscope can be used to analyze nanowires to better understand their structures, and the radial breathing mode of carbon nanotubes is commonly used to evaluate their diameter.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Raman active fibers, such as aramid and carbon, have vibrational modes that show a shift in Raman frequency with applied stress.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Polypropylene fibers exhibit similar shifts.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] In solid state chemistry and the bio-pharmaceutical industry, Raman spectroscopy can be used to not only identify active pharmaceutical ingredients (APIs), but to identify their polymorphic forms, if more than one exist.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] For example, the drug Cayston (aztreonam), marketed by Gilead Sciences for cystic fibrosis, can be identified and characterized by IR and Raman spectroscopy.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Using the correct polymorphic form in bio-pharmaceutical formulations is critical, since different forms have different physical properties, like solubility and melting point.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Raman spectroscopy has a wide variety of applications in biology and medicine.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] It has helped confirm the existence of low-frequency phonons in proteins and DNA, promoting studies of low-frequency collective motion in proteins and DNA and their biological functions.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Raman reporter molecules with olefin or alkyne moieties are being developed for tissue imaging with SERS-labeled antibodies.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Raman spectroscopy has also been used as a noninvasive technique for real-time, in situ biochemical characterization of wounds.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Multivariate analysis of Raman spectra has enabled development of a quantitative measure for wound healing progress.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Spatially offset Raman spectroscopy (SORS), which is less sensitive to surface layers than conventional Raman, can be used to discover counterfeit drugs without opening their packaging, and to non-invasively study biological tissue.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] A reason why Raman spectroscopy is useful in biological applications is because its results often do not face interference from water molecules, due to the fact that they have permanent dipole moments, and as a result, the Raman scattering cannot be picked up on.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] This is a large advantage, specifically in biological applications.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Raman spectroscopy also has a wide usage for studying biominerals.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Lastly, Raman gas analyzers have many practical applications, including real-time monitoring of anesthetic and respiratory gas mixtures during surgery.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Raman spectroscopy has been used in several research projects as a means to detect explosives from a safe distance using laser beams.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Raman spectroscopy is being further developed so it could be used in the clinical setting.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Raman4Clinic is a European organization that is working on incorporating Raman Spectroscopy techniques in the medical field.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] They are currently working on different projects, one of them being monitoring cancer using bodily fluids such as urine and blood samples which are easily accessible.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] This technique would be less stressful on the patients than constantly having to take biopsies which are not always risk free.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] In photovoltaics, Raman spectroscopy has gained more interest in the past few years demonstrating high efficacy in delivering important properties for such materials.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] This includes optoelectronic and physicochemical properties such as open circuit voltage, efficiency, and crystalline structure.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] This has been demonstrated with several photovoltaic technologies, including kesterite-based, CIGS devices, Monocrystalline silicon cells, and perovskites devices.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Raman spectroscopy is an efficient and non-destructive way to investigate works of art and cultural heritage artifacts, in part because it is a non-invasive process which can be applied *in situ*.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] It can be used to analyze the corrosion products on the surfaces of artifacts (statues, pottery, etc.), which can lend insight into the corrosive environments experienced by the artifacts.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The resulting spectra can also be compared to the spectra of surfaces that are cleaned or intentionally corroded, which can aid in determining the authenticity of valuable historical artifacts.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] It is capable of identifying individual pigments in paintings and their degradation products, which can provide insight into the working method of an artist in addition to aiding in authentication of paintings.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] It also gives information about the original state of the painting in cases where the pigments have degraded with age.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] In addition to paintings and artifacts, Raman spectroscopy can be used to investigate the chemical composition of historical documents (such as the Book of Kells), which can provide insight about the social and economic conditions when they were created.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] It also offers a noninvasive way to determine the best method of preservation or conservation of such cultural heritage artifacts, by providing insight into the causes behind deterioration.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The IRUG (Infrared and Raman Users Group) Spectral Database is a rigorously peer-reviewed online database of IR and Raman reference spectra for cultural heritage materials such as works of art, architecture, and archaeological artifacts.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The database is open for the general public to peruse, and includes interactive spectra for over a hundred different types of pigments and paints.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Raman spectroscopy offers several advantages for microscopic analysis.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Since it is a light scattering technique, specimens do not need to be fixed or sectioned.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Raman spectra can be collected from a very small volume (< 1 μm in diameter, < 10 μm in depth); these spectra allow the identification of species present in that volume.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Water does not generally interfere with Raman spectral analysis.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Thus, Raman spectroscopy is suitable for the microscopic examination of minerals, materials such as polymers and ceramics, cells, proteins and forensic trace evidence.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] A Raman microscope begins with a standard optical microscope, and adds an excitation laser, a monochromator or polychromator, and a sensitive detector (such as a charge-coupled device (CCD), or photomultiplier tube (PMT)).
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] FT-Raman has also been used with microscopes, typically in combination with near-infrared (NIR) laser excitation.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Ultraviolet microscopes and UV enhanced optics must be used when a UV laser source is used for Raman microspectroscopy.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] In *direct imaging* (also termed *global imaging* or *wide-field illumination*), the whole field of view is examined for light scattering integrated over a small range of wavenumbers (Raman shifts).
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] For instance, a wavenumber characteristic for cholesterol could be used to record the distribution of cholesterol within a cell culture.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] This technique is being used for the characterization of large-scale devices, mapping of different compounds and dynamics study.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] It has already been used for the characterization of graphene layers, J-aggregated dyes inside carbon nanotubes and multiple other 2D materials such as MoS2 and WSe2.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Since the excitation beam is dispersed over the whole field of view, those measurements can be done without damaging the sample.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The most common approach is *hyperspectral imaging* or *chemical imaging*, in which thousands of Raman spectra are acquired from all over the field of view by, for example, raster scanning of a focused laser beam through a sample.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The data can be used to generate images showing the location and amount of different components.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Having the full spectroscopic information available in every measurement spot has the advantage that several components can be mapped at the same time, including chemically similar and even polymorphic forms, which cannot be distinguished by detecting only one single wavenumber.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Furthermore, material properties such as stress and strain, crystal orientation, crystallinity and incorporation of foreign ions into crystal lattices (e.g., doping, solid solution series) can be determined from hyperspectral maps.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Taking the cell culture example, a hyperspectral image could show the distribution of cholesterol, as well as proteins, nucleic acids, and fatty acids.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Sophisticated signal- and image-processing techniques can be used to ignore the presence of water, culture media, buffers, and other interferences.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Because a Raman microscope is a diffraction-limited system, its spatial resolution depends on the wavelength of light, the numerical aperture of the focusing element, and — in the case of confocal microscopy — on the diameter of the confocal aperture.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] When operated in the visible to near-infrared range, a Raman microscope can achieve lateral resolutions of approx.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] 1 μm down to 250 nm, depending on the wavelength and type of objective lens (e.g., air *vs.* water or oil immersion lenses).
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The depth resolution (if not limited by the optical penetration depth of the sample) can range from 1–6 μm with the smallest confocal pinhole aperture to tens of micrometers when operated without a confocal pinhole.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Depending on the sample, the high laser power density due to microscopic focussing can have the benefit of enhanced photobleaching of molecules emitting interfering fluorescence.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] However, the laser wavelength and laser power have to be carefully selected for each type of sample to avoid its degradation.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Applications of Raman imaging range from materials sciences to biological studies.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] For each type of sample, the measurement parameters have to be individually optimized.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] For that reason, modern Raman microscopes are often equipped with several lasers offering different wavelengths, a set of objective lenses, and neutral density filters for tuning of the laser power reaching the sample.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Selection of the laser wavelength mainly depends on optical properties of the sample and on the aim of the investigation.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] For example, Raman microscopy of biological and medical specimens is often performed using red to near-infrared excitation (e.g., 785 nm, or 1,064 nm wavelength).
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Due to typically low absorbances of biological samples in this spectral range, the risk of damaging the specimen as well as autofluorescence emission are reduced, and high penetration depths into tissues can be achieved.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] However, the intensity of Raman scattering at long wavelengths is low (owing to the ω4 dependence of Raman scattering intensity), leading to long acquisition times.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] On the other hand, resonance Raman imaging of single-cell algae at 532 nm (green) can specifically probe the carotenoid distribution within a cell by a using low laser power of ~5 μW and only 100 ms acquisition time.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Raman scattering, specifically tip-enhanced Raman spectroscopy, produces high resolution hyperspectral images of single molecules, atoms, and DNA.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Raman scattering is polarization sensitive and can provide detailed information on symmetry of Raman active modes.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] While conventional Raman spectroscopy identifies chemical composition, polarization effects on Raman spectra can reveal information on the orientation of molecules in single crystals and anisotropic materials, e.g. strained plastic sheets, as well as the symmetry of vibrational modes.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Polarization–dependent Raman spectroscopy uses (plane) polarized laser excitation from a polarizer.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The Raman scattered light collected is passed through a second polarizer (called the analyzer) before entering the detector.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The analyzer is oriented either parallel or perpendicular to the polarization of the laser.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Spectra acquired with the analyzer set at both perpendicular and parallel to the excitation plane can be used to calculate the depolarization ratio.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Typically a polarization scrambler is placed between the analyzer and detector also.It is convenient in polarized Raman spectroscopy to describe the propagation and polarization directions using Porto's notation, described by and named after Brazilian physicist Sergio Pereira da Silva Porto.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] For isotropic solutions, the Raman scattering from each mode either retains the polarization of the laser or becomes partly or fully depolarized.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] If the vibrational mode involved in the Raman scattering process is totally symmetric then the polarization of the Raman scattering will be the same as that of the incoming laser beam.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] In the case that the vibrational mode is not totally symmetric then the polarization will be lost (scrambled) partially or totally, which is referred to as depolarization.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Hence polarized Raman spectroscopy can provide detailed information as to the symmetry labels of vibrational modes.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] In the solid state, polarized Raman spectroscopy can be useful in the study of oriented samples such as single crystals.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The polarizability of a vibrational mode is not equal along and across the bond.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Therefore, the intensity of the Raman scattering will be different when the laser's polarization is along and orthogonal to a particular bond axis.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] This effect can provide information on the orientation of molecules with a single crystal or material.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The spectral information arising from this analysis is often used to understand macro-molecular orientation in crystal lattices, liquid crystals or polymer samples.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The polarization technique is useful in understanding the connections between molecular symmetry, Raman activity, and peaks in the corresponding Raman spectra.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Polarized light in one direction only gives access to some Raman–active modes, but rotating the polarization gives access to other modes.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] If ${\textstyle \rho \geq {\frac {3}{4}}}$ , then the vibrations at that frequency are *depolarized*; meaning they are not totally symmetric.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Resonance Raman selection rules can be explained by the Kramers–Heisenberg equation using the Albrecht A and B terms, as demonstrated.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The polarizability operator connecting the initial and final states expresses the transition polarizability as a matrix element, as a function of the incidence frequency ω0.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The directions x, y, and z in the molecular frame are represented by the Cartesian tensor ρ and σ here.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Analyzing Raman excitation patterns requires the use of this equation, which is a sum-over-states expression for polarizability.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] This series of profiles illustrates the connection between a Raman active vibration's excitation frequency and intensity.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] This method takes into account sums over Franck-Condon's active vibrational states and provides insight into electronic absorption and emission spectra.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Nevertheless, the work highlights a flaw in the sum-over-states method, especially for large molecules like visible chromophores, which are commonly studied in Raman spectroscopy.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The difficulty arises from the potentially infinite number of intermediary steps needed.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] While lowering the sum at higher vibrational states can help tiny molecules get over this issue, larger molecules find it more challenging when there are more terms in the sum, particularly in the condensed phase when individual eigenstates cannot be resolved spectrally.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] To overcome this, two substitute techniques that do not require adding eigenstates can be considered.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Among these two methods are available: the transform method. and Heller's time-dependent approach.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The goal of both approaches is to take into consideration the frequency-dependent Raman cross-section σR(ω0) of a particular normal mode.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] At least 25 variations of Raman spectroscopy have been developed.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The usual purpose is to enhance the sensitivity (e.g., Surface-enhanced Raman spectroscopy (SERS)), to improve the spatial resolution (Raman microscopy), or to acquire very specific information (resonance Raman).
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Terms such as *spontaneous Raman spectroscopy* or *normal Raman spectroscopy* summarize Raman spectroscopy techniques based on Raman scattering by using normal far-field optics as described above.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Variants of normal Raman spectroscopy exist with respect to excitation-detection geometries, combination with other techniques, use of special (polarizing) optics and specific choice of excitation wavelengths for resonance enhancement.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Enhancement of Raman scattering is achieved by local electric-field enhancement by optical near-field effects (e.g. localized surface plasmons).
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Raman signal enhancements are achieved through non-linear optical effects, typically realized by mixing two or more wavelengths emitted by spatially and temporally synchronized pulsed lasers.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Morphologically Directed Raman Spectroscopy (MDRS) combines automated particle imaging and Raman microspectroscopy into a singular integrated platform in order to provide particle size, shape, and chemical identification.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Automated particle imaging determines the particle size and shape distributions of components within a blended sample from images of individual particles.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The information gathered from automated particle imaging is then utilized to direct the Raman spectroscopic analysis.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The Raman spectroscopic analytical process is performed on a randomly selected subset of the particles, allowing chemical identification of the sample's multiple components.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Tens of thousands of particles can be imaged in a matter of minutes using the MDRS method, making the process ideal for forensic analysis and investigating counterfeit pharmaceuticals and subsequent adjudications.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p02] Where, $\alpha$ is the 3x3 polarizability tensor.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p02] In the **double-harmonic approximations**, the potential energy is expanded to the **second order** near equilibrium (harmonic force fields), while polarizability, is truncated at **first order** in the normal coordinates.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p02] In practice, $\alpha$ can be calculated through analytical methods or by employing the finite difference method for energy under small perturbations in $\mathbf {F}$ .
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p02] Where M is the diagonal matrix of atomic masses and L is the matrix of orthonormal eigenvectors (normal modes).
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p02] Since the $\partial {\boldsymbol {\alpha }}/\partial \mathbf {R}$ is known from finite differences or gradient calculation, it will used to calculate $Q_{p}$ , and further to get the Raman activities.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p02] Since some thermodynamic calculations ignored in the harmonic approximation, DFT-calculated harmonic frequencies are systematically **too high**.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p02] For example, the B3LYP/TZVP scaling factor is 0.965.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p02] Before to calculating the static spectrum, the structure must be optimized to its lowest energy point using the same or an approximate DFT basis set/functional.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p02] The mentioned static (harmonic) method also has been integrated into the Gaussian software as default, using the keyword Opt Freq=Raman to calculate.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p02] The harmonic approximation methods ignore some non-harmonic calculations.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p02] As an alternative, *ab initio* or machine-learned molecular-dynamics trajectories provide dynamic Raman spectrum.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p02] At each time step, the real-time polarizability tensor ${\boldsymbol {\alpha }}(t)$ is calculated, from the isotropic and anisotropic components we mentioned as $\alpha _{\mathrm {iso} }(t)$ and $\alpha _{\mathrm {aniso} }(t)$ , there will obtained from dynamical trajectory.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p02] This expression is derived from the angular momentum averaging of scattered lights from the random molecular orientations.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p02] The factor 4/3 the iso/aniso probably contribution.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p02] The ratio show the information on the symmetry of the vibrational modes.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p02] So, from the time dependent polarizability tensor ${\boldsymbol {\alpha }}(t)$ , the isotropic and anisotropic time series can be obtained.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p02] Their autocorrelation functions are calculated, Fourier transformed, and finally combined using the rotational averaging method to generate the total Raman spectrum.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p02] This polarizability-autocorrelation Fourier transform method naturally integrates anharmonic coupling, temperature broadening, and the polarization effects.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p02] It is providing a realistic description of Raman spectroscopy beyond the harmonic approximation.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p02] In recent years, machine learning has become a powerful tool in Raman spectroscopy, enabling data-driven prediction and interpretation of spectral line characteristics.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p02] Such as machine learned interatomic potential and generative model.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/rayleigh-scattering] Rayleigh scattering results from the electric polarizability of the particles.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/rayleigh-scattering] The oscillating electric field of a light wave acts on the charges within a particle, causing them to move at the same frequency.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/rayleigh-scattering] The particle, therefore, becomes a small radiating dipole whose radiation we see as scattered light.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/rayleigh-scattering] The particles may be individual atoms or molecules; it can occur when light travels through transparent solids and liquids, but is most prominently seen in gases.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/rayleigh-scattering] Rayleigh scattering of sunlight in Earth's atmosphere causes diffuse sky radiation.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/rayleigh-scattering] Since blue light wavelengths scatter more, the diffuse sky seen in daytime is blue.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/rayleigh-scattering] At twilight the sunlight on the horizon is missing the scattered blue light wavelengths giving a yellowish to reddish hue to the low Sun.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/rayleigh-scattering] Scattering by particles with a size comparable to, or larger than, the wavelength of the light is typically treated by the Mie theory, the discrete dipole approximation and other computational techniques.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/rayleigh-scattering] Rayleigh scattering applies to particles that are small with respect to wavelengths of light, and that are optically "soft" (i.e., with a refractive index close to 1).
[src:raman-spectroscopy/rayleigh-scattering] Anomalous diffraction theory applies to optically soft but larger particles.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/rayleigh-scattering] In 1869, while attempting to determine whether any contaminants remained in the purified air he used for infrared experiments, John Tyndall discovered that bright light scattering off nanoscopic particulates was faintly blue-tinted.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/rayleigh-scattering] He conjectured that a similar scattering of sunlight gave the sky its blue hue, but he could not explain the preference for blue light, nor could atmospheric dust explain the intensity of the sky's color.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/rayleigh-scattering] In 1871, Lord Rayleigh published two papers on the color and polarization of skylight to quantify Tyndall's effect in water droplets in terms of the tiny particulates' volumes and refractive indices.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/rayleigh-scattering] In 1881, with the benefit of James Clerk Maxwell's 1865 proof of the electromagnetic nature of light, he showed that his equations followed from electromagnetism.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/rayleigh-scattering] In 1899, he showed that they applied to individual molecules, with terms containing particulate volumes and refractive indices replaced with terms for molecular polarizability.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/rayleigh-scattering] It was this paper that established the basic scientific model for the color of the sky.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/rayleigh-scattering] where *r* is the particle's radius, *λ* is the wavelength of the light and *x* is a dimensionless parameter that characterizes the particle's interaction with the incident radiation such that: Objects with x ≫ 1 act as geometric shapes, scattering light according to their projected area.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/rayleigh-scattering] At the intermediate x ≃ 1 of Mie scattering, interference effects develop through phase variations over the object's surface.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/rayleigh-scattering] Rayleigh scattering applies to the case when the scattering particle is very small (x ≪ 1, with a particle size < 1/10 of wavelength) and the whole surface re-radiates with the same phase.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/rayleigh-scattering] The wavelength dependence is characteristic of dipole scattering and the volume dependence will apply to any scattering mechanism.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/rayleigh-scattering] The major constituent of the atmosphere, nitrogen, has Rayleigh cross section of 5.1×10−31 m2 at a wavelength of 532 nm (green light).
[src:raman-spectroscopy/rayleigh-scattering] Over the length of one meter the fraction of light scattered can be approximated from the product of the cross-section and the particle density, that is number of particles per unit volume.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/rayleigh-scattering] For air at atmospheric pressure there are about 2×1025 molecules per cubic meter, and the fraction scattered will be 10−5 for every meter of travel.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/rayleigh-scattering] The expression above can also be written in terms of individual molecules by expressing the dependence on refractive index in terms of the molecular polarizability *α*, proportional to the dipole moment induced by the electric field of the light.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/rayleigh-scattering] The strong wavelength dependence of the Rayleigh scattering (~*λ*−4) means that shorter (blue) wavelengths are scattered more strongly than longer (red) wavelengths.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/rayleigh-scattering] This results in the indirect blue and violet light coming from all regions of the sky.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/rayleigh-scattering] The human eye responds to this wavelength combination as if it were a combination of blue and white light.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/rayleigh-scattering] Some of the scattering can also be from sulfate particles.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/rayleigh-scattering] For years after large Plinian eruptions, the blue cast of the sky is notably brightened by the persistent sulfate load of the stratospheric gases.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/rayleigh-scattering] Turner may owe their vivid red colours to the eruption of Mount Tambora in his lifetime.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/rayleigh-scattering] In locations with little light pollution, the moonlit night sky is also blue, because moonlight is reflected sunlight, with a slightly lower color temperature due to the brownish color of the Moon.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/rayleigh-scattering] The moonlit sky is not perceived as blue, however, because at low light levels human vision comes mainly from rod cells that do not produce any color perception (Purkinje effect).
[src:raman-spectroscopy/rayleigh-scattering] Rayleigh scattering is also an important mechanism of wave scattering in amorphous solids such as glass, and is responsible for acoustic wave damping and phonon damping in glasses and granular matter at low or not too high temperatures.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/rayleigh-scattering] This is because in glasses at higher temperatures the Rayleigh-type scattering regime is obscured by the anharmonic damping (typically with a ~*λ*−2 dependence on wavelength), which becomes increasingly more important as the temperature rises.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/rayleigh-scattering] Rayleigh scattering is an important component of the scattering of optical signals in optical fibers.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/rayleigh-scattering] Silica fibers are glasses, disordered materials with microscopic variations of density and refractive index.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/rayleigh-scattering] where *n* is the refraction index, *p* is the photoelastic coefficient of the glass, *k* is the Boltzmann constant, and *β* is the isothermal compressibility.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/rayleigh-scattering] *T*f is a *fictive temperature*, representing the temperature at which the density fluctuations are "frozen" in the material.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/rayleigh-scattering] Rayleigh-type *λ*−4 scattering can also be exhibited by porous materials.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/rayleigh-scattering] An example is the strong optical scattering by nanoporous materials.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/rayleigh-scattering] The strong contrast in refractive index between pores and solid parts of sintered alumina results in very strong scattering, with light completely changing direction each five micrometers on average.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/rayleigh-scattering] The *λ*−4-type scattering is caused by the nanoporous structure (a narrow pore size distribution around ~70 nm) obtained by sintering monodispersive alumina powder.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] SERS from pyridine adsorbed on electrochemically roughened silver was first observed by Martin Fleischmann, Patrick J.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] James McQuillan at the Department of Chemistry at the University of Southampton, UK in 1973.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] The 40th Anniversary of the first observation of the SERS effect has been marked by the Royal Society of Chemistry by the award of a National Chemical Landmark plaque to the University of Southampton.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] In 1977, two groups independently noted that the concentration of scattering species could not account for the enhanced signal and each proposed a mechanism for the observed enhancement.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] Their theories are still accepted as explaining the SERS effect.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] Jeanmaire and Richard Van Duyne proposed an electromagnetic effect, while Albrecht and Creighton proposed a charge-transfer effect.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] Rufus Ritchie, of Oak Ridge National Laboratory's Health Sciences Research Division, predicted the existence of the surface plasmon.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] The exact mechanism of the enhancement effect of SERS is still a matter of debate in the literature.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] There are two primary theories and while their mechanisms differ substantially, distinguishing them experimentally has not been straightforward.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] The electromagnetic theory proposes the excitation of localized surface plasmons, while the chemical theory proposes the formation of charge-transfer complexes.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] The chemical theory is based on resonance Raman spectroscopy, in which the frequency coincidence (or resonance) of the incident photon energy and electron transition greatly enhances Raman scattering intensity.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] Research in 2015 on a more powerful extension of the SERS technique called SLIPSERS (Slippery Liquid-Infused Porous SERS) has further supported the EM theory.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] The increase in intensity of the Raman signal for adsorbates on particular surfaces occurs because of an enhancement in the electric field provided by the surface.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] When the incident light in the experiment strikes the surface, localized surface plasmons are excited.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] The field enhancement is greatest when the plasmon frequency, ωp, is in resonance with the radiation ( $\omega =\omega _{p}/{\sqrt {3}}$ for spherical particles).
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] In order for scattering to occur, the plasmon oscillations must be perpendicular to the surface; if they are in-plane with the surface, no scattering will occur.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] It is because of this requirement that roughened surfaces or arrangements of nanoparticles are typically employed in SERS experiments as these surfaces provide an area on which these localized collective oscillations can occur.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] SERS enhancement can occur even when an excited molecule is relatively far apart from the surface which hosts metallic nanoparticles enabling surface plasmon phenomena.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] The light incident on the surface can excite a variety of phenomena in the surface, yet the complexity of this situation can be minimized by surfaces with features much smaller than the wavelength of the light, as only the dipolar contribution will be recognized by the system.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] The dipolar term contributes to the plasmon oscillations, which leads to the enhancement.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] The SERS effect is so pronounced because the field enhancement occurs twice.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] First, the field enhancement magnifies the intensity of incident light, which will excite the Raman modes of the molecule being studied, therefore increasing the signal of the Raman scattering.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] The Raman signal is then further magnified by the surface due to the same mechanism that excited the incident light, resulting in a greater increase in the total output.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] At each stage the electric field is enhanced as E2, for a total enhancement of E4.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] The enhancement is not equal for all frequencies.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] For those frequencies for which the Raman signal is only slightly shifted from the incident light, both the incident laser light and the Raman signal can be near resonance with the plasmon frequency, leading to the E4 enhancement.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] When the frequency shift is large, the incident light and the Raman signal cannot both be on resonance with ωp, thus the enhancement at both stages cannot be maximal.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] The choice of surface metal is also dictated by the plasmon resonance frequency.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] Visible and near-infrared radiation (NIR) are used to excite Raman modes.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] Silver and gold are typical metals for SERS experiments because their plasmon resonance frequencies fall within these wavelength ranges, providing maximal enhancement for visible and NIR light.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] Copper's absorption spectrum also falls within the range acceptable for SERS experiments.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] Platinum and palladium nanostructures also display plasmon resonance within visible and NIR frequencies.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] Resonance Raman spectroscopy explains the huge enhancement of Raman scattering intensity.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] Intermolecular and intramolecular charge transfers significantly enhance Raman spectrum peaks.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] In particular, the enhancement is huge for species adsorbing the metal surface due to the high-intensity charge transfers from the metal surface with wide band to the adsorbing species.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] This resonance Raman enhancement is dominant in SERS for species on small nanoclusters with considerable band gaps, because surface plasmon appears only in metal surface with near-zero band gaps.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] This chemical mechanism probably occurs in concert with the electromagnetic mechanism for metal surface.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] While SERS can be performed in colloidal solutions, today the most common method for performing SERS measurements is by depositing a liquid sample onto a silicon or glass surface with a nanostructured noble metal surface.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] While the first experiments were performed on electrochemically roughened silver, now surfaces are often prepared using a distribution of metal nanoparticles on the surface as well as using lithography or porous silicon as a support.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] Two dimensional silicon nanopillars decorated with silver have also been used to create SERS active substrates.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] The most common metals used for plasmonic surfaces in visible light SERS are silver and gold; however, aluminium has recently been explored as an alternative plasmonic material, because its plasmon band is in the UV region, contrary to silver and gold.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] Hence, there is great interest in using aluminium for UV SERS.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] It has, however, surprisingly also been shown to have a large enhancement in the infrared, which is not fully understood.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] In the current decade, it has been recognized that the cost of SERS substrates must be reduced in order to become a commonly used analytical chemistry measurement technique.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] To meet this need, plasmonic paper has experienced widespread attention in the field, with highly sensitive SERS substrates being formed through approaches such as soaking, in-situ synthesis, screen printing and inkjet printing.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] The shape and size of the metal nanoparticles strongly affect the strength of the enhancement because these factors influence the ratio of absorption and scattering events.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] There is an ideal size for these particles, and an ideal surface thickness for each experiment.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] If concentration and particle size can be tuned better for each experiment this will go a long way in the cost reduction of substrates.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] Particles that are too large allow the excitation of multipoles, which are nonradiative.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] As only the dipole transition leads to Raman scattering, the higher-order transitions will cause a decrease in the overall efficiency of the enhancement.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] Particles that are too small lose their electrical conductance and cannot enhance the field.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] When the particle size approaches a few atoms, the definition of a plasmon does not hold, as there must be a large collection of electrons to oscillate together.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] An ideal SERS substrate must possess high uniformity and high field enhancement.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] Such substrates can be fabricated on a wafer scale and label-free superresolution microscopy has also been demonstrated using the fluctuations of surface enhanced Raman scattering signal on such highly uniform, high-performance plasmonic metasurfaces.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] Due to their unique physical and chemical properties, two-dimensional (2D) materials have gained significant attention as alternative substrates for surface-enhanced Raman spectroscopy (SERS).
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] The use of 2D materials as SERS substrates offers several advantages over traditional metal substrates, including high sensitivity, reproducibility, and chemical stability.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] Graphene is one of the most widely studied 2D materials for SERS applications.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] Graphene has a high surface area, high electron mobility, and excellent chemical stability, making it an attractive substrate for SERS.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] Graphene-based SERS sensors have also been shown to be highly reproducible and stable, making them attractive for real-world applications.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] In addition to graphene, other 2D materials, especially MXenes, have also been investigated for SERS applications.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] MXenes have a high surface area, good electrical conductivity, and chemical stability, making them attractive for SERS applications.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] As a result, MXene-based SERS sensors have been used to detect various analytes, including organic molecules, drugs and their metabolites.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] As research and development continue, 2D materials-based SERS sensors will likely be more widely used in various industries, including environmental monitoring, healthcare, and food safety.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] SERS substrates are used to detect the presence of low-abundance biomolecules, and can therefore detect proteins in bodily fluids.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] Early detection of pancreatic cancer biomarkers was accomplished using SERS-based immunoassay approach.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] This technology has been utilized to detect urea and blood plasma label free in human serum and may become the next generation in cancer detection and screening.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] SERS is a powerful technique for determining structural information about molecular systems.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] It has found a wide range of applications in ultra-sensitive chemical sensing and environmental analyses.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] A review of the present and future applications of SERS was published in 2020.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] The term *surface enhanced Raman spectroscopy* implies that it provides the same information that traditional Raman spectroscopy does, simply with a greatly enhanced signal.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] While the spectra of most SERS experiments are similar to the non-surface enhanced spectra, there are often differences in the number of modes present.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] Additional modes not found in the traditional Raman spectrum can be present in the SERS spectrum, while other modes can disappear.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] The modes observed in any spectroscopic experiment are dictated by the symmetry of the molecules and are usually summarized by Selection rules.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] When molecules are adsorbed to a surface, the symmetry of the system can change, slightly modifying the symmetry of the molecule, which can lead to differences in mode selection.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] One common way in which selection rules are modified arises from the fact that many molecules that have a center of symmetry lose that feature when adsorbed to a surface.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] The loss of a center of symmetry eliminates the requirements of the mutual exclusion rule, which dictates that modes can only be either Raman or infrared active.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] Thus modes that would normally appear only in the infrared spectrum of the free molecule can appear in the SERS spectrum.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] A molecule's symmetry can be changed in different ways depending on the orientation in which the molecule is attached to the surface.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] In some experiments, it is possible to determine the orientation of adsorption to the surface from the SERS spectrum, as different modes will be present depending on how the symmetry is modified.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] Remote surface-enhanced Raman spectroscopy (SERS) consists of using metallic nanowaveguides supporting propagating surface plasmon polaritons (SPPs) to perform SERS at a distant location different to that of the incident laser.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] Propagating SPPs supported by nanowires has been used to show the remote excitation., as well as the remote detection of SERS.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] Different plasmonic systems have already been used to show Raman detection of biomolecules in vivo in cells and remote excitation of surface catalytic reactions.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] SERS-based immunoassays can be used for detection of low-abundance biomarkers.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] For example, antibodies and gold particles can be used to quantify proteins in serum with high sensitivity and specificity.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] SERS can be used to target specific DNA and RNA sequences using a combination of gold and silver nanoparticles and Raman-active dyes, such as Cy3.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] Specific single nucleotide polymorphisms (SNP) can be identified using this technique.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] The gold nanoparticles facilitate the formation of a silver coating on the dye-labelled regions of DNA or RNA, allowing SERS to be performed.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] This has several potential applications: For example, Cao et al. report that gene sequences for HIV, Ebola, Hepatitis, and Bacillus Anthracis can be uniquely identified using this technique.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] Each spectrum was specific, which is advantageous over fluorescence detection; some fluorescent markers overlap and interfere with other gene markers.
[src:raman-spectroscopy/surface-enhanced-raman-spectroscopy] The advantage of this technique to identify gene sequences is that several Raman dyes are commercially available, which could lead to the development of non-overlapping probes for gene detection.
